ion and the First World War respectively, and sharing a political inheritance of Scottish Enlightenment scepticism, Austen's and Woolf's rigorous critiques of the dangers of mental vision unchecked by facts is more timely than ever in the current world dominated by fundamentalist neo-liberal, religious and nationalist belief systems.Key FeaturesThe book uses close readings from Sense and Sensibility, Mrs Dalloway, Emma, The Waves, Persuasion and The Years to demonstrate the materialist sensibilities of Austen and WoolfIt traces the anti-individualism of their view of self and consciousness as deriving from embodied experienceEach chapter foregrounds the constitutive interrelationship of things, people, social and physical worldsThe book reconceptualises a progressive view of realism - worldly realism - drawing upon Jacques Rancière's thesis that a new democratic aesthetic regime is inaugurated around the end of the eighteenth century  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107814030 cprintz978147441913040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474423533zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474423533zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474423533/original  a978-3-11-078140-3 Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA